{"parentUuid":"b9d7b21a-7b44-4250-9ca9-dff9553d6587","isSidechain":false,"userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/d43103/Workspace/projects/javis","sessionId":"2d297878-1c18-4c40-972b-607e2d34ddc2","version":"2.1.45","gitBranch":"main","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":"upstream proxy ые╝ ьХИэХШыКФ ьЭ┤ьЬаыКФ ыДИым┤ ызОьЭА ыЭ╝ьЭ┤ы╕МыЯмыжмъ░А ьЮИьЦ┤ьДЬ?"},"uuid":"2752c6b7-ab80-4fa6-9a06-5a36f13ce26d","timestamp":"2026-02-18T16:43:17.504Z","thinkingMetadata":{"maxThinkingTokens":31999},"permissionMode":"default"}
{"parentUuid":"2752c6b7-ab80-4fa6-9a06-5a36f13ce26d","isSidechain":false,"userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/d43103/Workspace/projects/javis","sessionId":"2d297878-1c18-4c40-972b-607e2d34ddc2","version":"2.1.45","gitBranch":"main","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01Hb67efvfMgsSqN6iR17KMQ","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user is asking why Context7 doesn't implement upstream proxy functionality like JFrog does. This is an interesting architectural/design question. Let me think through the reasons.\n\nThere are several reasons why Context7 might not implement real-time upstream fetching:1. **Volume/Scale**: There are millions of npm packages - fetching and parsing docs for any arbitrary package on-demand is expensive2. **Quality control**: Not all packages have good documentation - curation ensures quality3. **Parsing complexity**: Documentation comes in many formats (JSDoc, TypeDoc, ReadTheDocs, GitHub wikis, etc.) - you need parsers/processors for each format4. **Cost**: Real-time crawling and LLM processing for unknown libraries would be expensive at scale5. \n\nThe latency problem is another big factorтАФreal-time fetching and processing would slow down tool responses too much. Plus, many packages simply don't have adequate documentation beyond a README, so there's a quality tradeoff. I can't know the exact reasoning behind Context7's product decisions, but the core constraints are probably scale, the diversity of documentation formats, response latency, and the quality benefits of curating a focused set of packages.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":74,"cache_read_input_tokens":42153,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":74},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"}},"requestId":"req_011CYFsPYGG5ivRHCjm8svYp","type":"assistant","uuid":"386b699a-8ac